<portion>
  <section1 id="sExcl">
	<secTitle>Exclamations and Greetings</secTitle>
	<p>
	<content>This section considers various types of common utterances which are not complete sentences.  We will deal with greetings, interjections and exclamations in turn.</content>
	</p>
<section2 id="sExclGreet">
	<secTitle>Greetings</secTitle>
<p><content>Greetings typically consist of a particular word or phrase, either standing alone or followed by a name or nominal phrase describing the peson or animal being greeted.  Some are full sentences or full questions, such as </content> <langData>How do you do? </langData><langData>How are you? </langData> <content> and </content><langData>Have a good day!</langData> <content> which do not need to be treated separately.  Some examples of English greetings are:
</content></p>
			<ol>
				<li>
					<content>Hi!</content>
				</li>
				<li>
					<content>Howdy!</content>
				</li>
				<li>
					<content>Hello, Jill.</content>
				</li>
				<li>
					<content>Goodby.</content>
				</li>
				<li>
					<content>Good day, sir.</content>
				</li>
				<li>
					<content>Good morning, Bob.</content>
				</li>
				<li>
					<content>Good afternoon.</content>
				</li>
				<li>
					<content>Good evening.</content>
				</li>
				<li>
					<content>Good night, sweet baby.</content>
				</li>
			</ol>
<p><content>Examples of greetings in </content><langName/> <content> include:</content></p>
			<example>
				<interlinear exampleLoc="excl/greetExample"/>
			</example>
</section2>
<section2 id="sExclIntj">
	<secTitle>Interjections</secTitle>
<p><content>Interjections typically consist of a particular word or phrase that is used alone, usually with an exclamation point following it.  Though many of the words in interjections are not used in any other situation, regular adjectives are also used in this way.  Some examples of interjections in English are:
</content></p>
			<ol>
				<li>
					<content>Ouch!</content>
				</li>
				<li>
					<content>Gross!</content>
				</li>
				<li>
					<content>Cool!</content>
				</li>
				<li>
					<content>Jumping Jehoshaphat!</content>
				</li>
				<li>
					<content>Jiminy Cricket!</content>
				</li>
			</ol>
<p><content>Examples of interjections in </content><langName/> <content> include:</content></p>
			<example>
				<interlinear exampleLoc="excl/intjExample"/>
			</example>
<p><content>Yes and No answers to questions will be treated similarly to interjections.  </content><langName/><content> uses the following words to express these answers:</content></p>
<example>
<table border="1">
					<headerRow>
						<headerCol>
							<langName/>
						</headerCol>
						<headerCol>meaning</headerCol>
					</headerRow>
					<row>
						<col exampleLoc="excl/yesExample"/>
						<col>
							<content>yes</content>
						</col>
					</row>
					<row>
						<col exampleLoc="excl/noExample"/>
						<col>
							<content>no</content>
						</col>
					</row>
</table>
</example>
</section2>
<section2 id="sExclExcl">
	<secTitle>Exclamations</secTitle>
<p><content>Exclamations typically consist of a particular word, such as </content><langData>how</langData><content> in English, followed by an adjective phrase and usually punctuated with an exclamation point.  English examples include:</content></p>
<ol>
	  <li><content>How awful for you!</content></li>
	  <li><content>How nice!</content></li>
	  <li><content>How wonderful that your family could come!</content></li>
</ol>
<p><content>Examples of exclamations in </content><langName/><content> include:</content></p>
			<example>
				<interlinear exampleLoc="excl/exclExample"/>
			</example>
<p show="swExclMNo"><langName/><content> does not have a special word which marks exclamations of this type, so they are no different than the interjections consisting of adjectives in the previous section.</content></p>
<p show="swExclMYes"><langName/> <content> has one or more special words which signal an exclamation which occur </content><case element="excl" attr="exclMPos">
<caseText value="before">before</caseText>
<caseText value="after">after</caseText>
<caseText value="either">on either side of</caseText>
<caseText value="both">on both sides of</caseText>
</case><content> the adjective phrase.  These exclamation marker words are:</content></p>
<example show="swExclMYes"><table border="1">
<headerRow>
	<headerCol>Exclamation Markers</headerCol>
</headerRow>
	<row>
		<col exampleLoc="excl/exclMExample"></col>
	</row>
</table>
</example>
<p show="swExclMYesEitherNo"><content>There are separate sets words which can occur on each side of the adjective phrase.</content></p>
<p show="swExclMYesEitherYes"><content>All of the words may occur on either side of the adjective phrase.</content></p>
</section2>
  </section1>
